<section class="rat" aria-labelledby="rat-title">
  <div class="container rat__inner">
    <div class="rat__head">
      <div class="eyebrow">
        <span class="tag">03 / 07</span>
        <span class="sep"></span>
        <span>why compile PHP at all</span>
      </div>
      <h2 id="rat-title" class="h-section rat__title">
        The interesting half of PHP<br />
        <span class="mark-dim">is the half you can actually reason about.</span>
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="rat__cols">
      <div class="rat__prose">
        <p>
          Most discussion of "fast PHP" lands on JIT, opcache, or FFI. Those are
          worthwhile, but they all accept the same premise: your program is still a
          PHP program at runtime, running inside a very clever interpreter.
        </p>
        <p>
          elephc takes the other position. A large, boring, valuable subset of modern
          PHP — typed parameters, typed returns, classes, enums, exceptions — is already
          the same shape as Rust, C#, or Swift. It is statically analysable, ahead-of-time
          compilable, and doesn't need a VM to run. It only runs inside one because,
          historically, nobody wrote the compiler.
        </p>
      </div>

      <aside class="rat__quote" aria-label="Thesis">
        <div class="rat__quote-mark mono" aria-hidden="true">{`{ }`}</div>
        <blockquote>
          <p>
            Keep your framework on PHP.<br />
            Isolate the static, performance-sensitive paths.<br />
            Compile those into standalone binaries,<br />
            and drop them in.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
        <footer class="rat__cite mono">elephc — the whole pitch, in four lines.</footer>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <div class="rat__principles">
      <div class="rat__p">
        <div class="rat__p-num mono">i</div>
        <h3 class="rat__p-h">A honest line between static and dynamic.</h3>
        <p>elephc refuses to guess. If a call target, type, or dispatch can't be resolved at compile time, the compiler says so — it doesn't insert a fallback that will bite you at 3 a.m.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rat__p">
        <div class="rat__p-num mono">ii</div>
        <h3 class="rat__p-h">A single artefact, with predictable cost.</h3>
        <p>One executable. No dynamic loader chasing .so files. No warm-up period. Startup is measured in single-digit milliseconds, not seconds, because there is nothing to warm.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rat__p">
        <div class="rat__p-num mono">iii</div>
        <h3 class="rat__p-h">A compiler you could read in an afternoon.</h3>
        <p>~45k lines of Rust, with 1,800+ tests and no external runtime. The pipeline is short enough that a motivated engineer can trace a single function from .php to its generated .text bytes in one sitting.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

